      <h1>Comorbidities</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Co-occurring conditions and gambling disorder — and what they mean
        for prevention.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Why comorbidity belongs in a prevention conversation</h2>
      <p>
        When a person experiences a gambling problem, it rarely travels
        alone. The same individual is far more likely than the general
        population to also be living with a substance use disorder,
        depression, an anxiety disorder, attention difficulties, or thoughts
        of suicide. For clinicians, that clustering shapes treatment. For
        prevention professionals, it points somewhere just as important:
        the risk and protective factors that drive gambling harm overlap
        heavily with those that drive other behavioral-health problems —
        which means gambling can, and should, be prevented within the
        systems already working on substance use and mental health.
      </p>
      <p>
        Gambling harm exists on a spectrum, from no risk through low-risk
        recreational play to problem gambling and gambling disorder.
        Comorbidity is part of what makes that spectrum matter for
        prevention: co-occurring conditions can both raise the risk that
        gambling becomes harmful and be worsened by it. This page reviews
        what co-occurs and how often, then turns to the practical question
        prevention professionals actually face — what to do with that
        knowledge.
      </p>
      <p>
        A note on language: this page uses person-first, non-stigmatizing
        terms (a person with a gambling problem, not "a gambler"; gambling
        disorder rather than older labels) and treats gambling harm as a
        continuum rather than an all-or-nothing condition.
      </p>

      <h2>A behavioral addiction, not an outlier</h2>
      <p>
        In 2013, with the publication of the DSM-5, the American
        Psychiatric Association moved gambling disorder out of the
        "Impulse-Control Disorders Not Elsewhere Classified" category —
        where it had sat since 1980 alongside conditions such as
        kleptomania and pyromania — and placed it within
        "Substance-Related and Addictive Disorders" (American Psychiatric
        Association, 2013; APA Psychiatric News, 2013). This
        reclassification is preserved in the DSM-5-TR (American
        Psychiatric Association, 2022). Gambling disorder is, to date, the
        only behavioral (non-substance) addiction recognized in the main
        text of the manual.
      </p>
      <p>
        This was not a clerical change. The chair of the DSM-5 work group
        on substance-related and addictive disorders explained the
        evidence as showing that addiction is fundamentally a brain
        reward-system disorder — and that the system can be repeatedly
        activated whether the trigger is gambling, alcohol, or another
        substance; functional brain imaging finds the same reward-related
        regions activated by gambling cues and by drug cues (APA
        Psychiatric News, 2013). The reclassification reflected the
        accumulated evidence of shared reward-system neurocircuitry,
        similar behavior patterns (craving, tolerance expressed as needing
        larger wagers, loss of control), high mutual comorbidity, shared
        genetic and neurobiological underpinnings, and the effectiveness
        of common treatment approaches such as cognitive-behavioral
        therapy and 12-step models (APA Psychiatric News, 2013; SAMHSA,
        2014).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Why this matters for prevention.</strong> If gambling
        disorder is mechanistically an addiction, then the prevention
        science built around substance use applies. The same constructs —
        reward sensitivity, impulsivity, early onset, coping motives,
        environmental availability — are in play. Practitioners do not
        need a separate theory of gambling prevention; they need to extend
        the one they already use. As SAMHSA's advisory notes, the
        reclassification itself may improve treatment coverage, diagnostic
        accuracy, and screening efforts (SAMHSA, 2014). The same logic
        extends upstream to prevention.
      </p>

      <h2>What co-occurs, and how often</h2>
      <p>
        Two kinds of evidence anchor the comorbidity picture: large
        nationally representative population surveys, and meta-analyses
        that pool many studies. They converge on the same conclusion —
        co-occurrence is the rule, not the exception.
      </p>

      <h3>Co-occurrence is nearly universal</h3>
      <p>
        In the U.S. National Comorbidity Survey Replication (NCS-R), a
        nationally representative sample, <strong>96.3 percent</strong> of
        respondents who met lifetime criteria for pathological gambling
        also met criteria for at least one other lifetime psychiatric
        disorder, and <strong>64.3 percent</strong> had three or more
        co-occurring disorders (Kessler et al., 2008). In that survey,
        lifetime problem gambling (at least one symptom) was 2.3 percent
        and pathological gambling 0.6 percent — a small share of the
        population carrying a very heavy load of co-occurring conditions.
      </p>

      <h3>The most common co-occurring conditions</h3>
      <p>
        The most-cited population meta-analysis of community samples found
        the following mean prevalence rates of co-occurring conditions
        among people with problem or pathological gambling (Lorains,
        Cowlishaw &amp; Thomas, 2011):
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Co-occurring condition</th>
              <th scope="col">Mean prevalence among problem / pathological gamblers</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Nicotine dependence</td><td>60.1%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Any substance use disorder</td><td>57.5%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Any mood disorder</td><td>37.9%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Any anxiety disorder</td><td>37.4%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Alcohol use disorder</td><td>28.1%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        A separate U.S. national survey — the National Epidemiologic
        Survey on Alcohol and Related Conditions (NESARC) — found even
        higher rates among people diagnosed with pathological gambling:
        <strong>73.2 percent</strong> had an alcohol use disorder,
        <strong>38.1 percent</strong> a drug use disorder,
        <strong>60.4 percent</strong> nicotine dependence,
        <strong>49.6 percent</strong> a mood disorder,
        <strong>41.3 percent</strong> an anxiety disorder, and
        <strong>60.8 percent</strong> a personality disorder (Petry,
        Stinson &amp; Grant, 2005, as reported in SAMHSA, 2014).
        Differences between the two estimates reflect different samples
        (community vs. diagnosed) and methods; the consistent message is
        that substance use, mood, and anxiety conditions co-occur with
        gambling problems at rates many times those in the general
        population.
      </p>
      <p>
        The relationship with substance use runs in both directions.
        SAMHSA reports that roughly <strong>10 to 15 percent</strong> of
        people with a substance use disorder may also have a gambling
        problem (SAMHSA, 2014) — which is why substance-use settings are
        a high-yield place to screen.
      </p>

      <h3>Attention and impulse-related conditions</h3>
      <p>
        Attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) co-occurs with
        gambling problems more often than chance. Among treatment-seeking
        problem gamblers, studies have reported adult ADHD prevalence in
        the range of roughly 20 to 40 percent, and people with ADHD are
        several times more likely to gamble problematically than those
        without; those with co-occurring adult ADHD tend to have more
        severe gambling problems and more additional psychiatric
        comorbidity (Brandt &amp; Fischer, 2019). Shared impulsivity is a
        plausible common thread — and a shared prevention target.
      </p>

      <h3>Reading these numbers responsibly</h3>
      <p>
        Comorbidity figures vary with the sample (general population vs.
        treatment-seeking vs. diagnosed), the diagnostic criteria and era
        (much research used DSM-IV "pathological gambling"), and the
        screening tools used. Treatment-seeking samples show the highest
        rates because severity and help-seeking travel together. For
        prevention purposes, the precise percentage matters less than the
        direction and magnitude: co-occurrence is common, substantial, and
        bidirectional.
      </p>

      <h2>Suicide risk</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling disorder carries an elevated risk of suicidal ideation
        and suicide attempts — a fact prevention professionals should hold
        plainly and without alarm. The association is well documented
        (SAMHSA, 2014). In a case-control study in the general Swedish
        population, suicide attempts were about twice as common among
        people with problem gambling (6.6 percent) as among matched
        controls (3.3 percent), and suicidal ideation was likewise roughly
        twice as common (21.2 percent vs. 11.2 percent) (Sundqvist &amp;
        Wennberg, 2021). Risk is highest among people in treatment and
        among those whose gambling co-occurs with depression, substance
        use, or acute financial crisis (SAMHSA, 2014).
      </p>
      <p>
        Co-occurring conditions appear central to this risk. After
        accounting for other psychiatric conditions, much of the
        gambling–suicide association is shared with those conditions —
        which is precisely why an integrated view matters: addressing
        depression, substance use, and financial harm together does more
        to reduce suicide risk than treating any one factor in isolation
        (Sundqvist &amp; Wennberg, 2021).
      </p>
      <p>
        For prevention practice, the takeaway is concrete: gambling
        belongs in suicide-prevention awareness, and suicide-risk
        awareness belongs in gambling prevention. Gatekeeper training,
        screening protocols, and warm-handoff referral pathways should
        account for gambling as a contributing stressor. If a person is
        in crisis, the <strong>988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline</strong>
        (call, text, or chat <a href="tel:988">988</a>) is available
        around the clock.
      </p>

      <h2>Shared risk and protective factors</h2>
      <p>
        Comorbidity is not a coincidence. Gambling problems cluster with
        other behavioral-health conditions because they grow from
        overlapping soil. For prevention, this shared etiology is the
        whole point: factors that raise risk for one condition often raise
        it for several, and the protective factors that buffer one tend to
        buffer many.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Shared risk factors</strong> documented across gambling
        and other behavioral-health conditions include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Impulsivity and reward sensitivity</strong> — trait
          impulsivity in childhood is associated with the later onset of
          both pathological gambling and substance use disorders (SAMHSA,
          2014), and shared reward-system neurobiology underlies the
          DSM-5 grouping of gambling with substance addictions (APA
          Psychiatric News, 2013).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Early onset</strong> — beginning gambling young, like
          early substance use, is associated with greater later risk.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) and trauma</strong>
          — cumulative childhood adversity raises the risk of disordered
          gambling, with people reporting three or more ACE types
          substantially more likely to report disordered gambling;
          emotion dysregulation appears to mediate part of this pathway
          (Poole et al., 2017). ACEs are an established, cross-cutting
          risk factor for substance use and mental-health conditions
          broadly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Co-occurring mental-health symptoms</strong> —
          depression and anxiety can both precede gambling problems (as
          drivers of "escape" gambling) and follow them, reflecting a
          reciprocal relationship.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Male sex, younger age, lower income and socioeconomic
          status, and minority status</strong> show associations with
          gambling problems in national data (SAMHSA, 2014), mirroring
          social-determinant patterns seen across behavioral health.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>Protective factors</strong> are correspondingly
        cross-cutting: strong social connectedness and family bonding,
        emotion-regulation and coping skills, school and community
        engagement, accurate understanding of risk and probability, and
        policy- and environment-level conditions that limit harmful
        exposure. None of these is gambling-specific — which is exactly
        why a single set of protective-factor investments can pay off
        across multiple outcomes.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The prevention implication is direct.</strong> When
        prevention works on shared risk and protective factors — building
        coping and emotion-regulation skills, addressing trauma,
        strengthening connectedness, reducing harmful availability — it
        is simultaneously gambling prevention, substance-use prevention,
        and mental-health promotion. Gambling does not require a parallel
        prevention system; it requires inclusion in the one that already
        targets these common factors.
      </p>

      <h2>What this means for prevention</h2>

      <h3>Integrate gambling into behavioral-health prevention</h3>
      <p>
        The comorbidity and shared-factor evidence makes the case for
        <strong>integrated behavioral-health prevention</strong>: planning
        that addresses substance use, mental health, and gambling together
        rather than in silos. SAMHSA's broader behavioral-health framework
        already treats integration and "whole-person" care as priorities,
        and applies a "no wrong door" principle — people entering care for
        one behavioral-health condition should be screened for others
        (SAMHSA, <em>Co-Occurring Disorders</em>). Extending that principle
        to gambling is a small, evidence-aligned step, not a new mandate.
      </p>
      <p>
        Practically, integration means: naming gambling in substance-use
        and mental-health prevention curricula; including gambling risk
        and protective factors in community needs assessments and logic
        models; ensuring coalitions addressing youth substance use also
        consider youth gambling and the increasingly blurred line between
        gaming and gambling; and training the prevention workforce to
        recognize gambling as a behavioral-health issue within their
        existing scope.
      </p>

      <h3>Screen and identify early (SBIRT-style approaches)</h3>
      <p>
        Few people seek help for gambling directly — only about 10 percent
        of those with a gambling problem do — and many present for other
        complaints such as stress, insomnia, depression, anxiety, or
        substance use instead (SAMHSA, 2014). There are no outward
        physical signs. That makes <strong>routine screening</strong>
        essential, particularly in settings serving people with the
        comorbidities described above.
      </p>
      <p>
        Brief, validated screens make this feasible. The two-item
        <strong>Lie/Bet</strong> questionnaire asks about needing to bet
        more over time and about lying to people important to the person
        about how much they gambled; a positive response warrants a
        longer tool such as the South Oaks Gambling Screen or a NODS-based
        screen (SAMHSA, 2014). The ICRG's <strong>Brief Biosocial
        Gambling Screen (BBGS)</strong> is another short, freely available
        option (ICRG, <em>Brief Biosocial Gambling Screen</em>). These
        fit naturally into an <strong>SBIRT</strong> logic — Screening,
        Brief Intervention, and Referral to Treatment — the same
        early-identification model the prevention and behavioral-health
        workforce already applies to alcohol and other drugs. Embedding a
        gambling item or short screen alongside existing substance-use
        screening operationalizes "no wrong door."
      </p>

      <h3>Build on systems that already exist</h3>
      <p>
        Because the risk factors, neurobiology, and care pathways overlap,
        the substance-use and mental-health prevention infrastructure —
        coalitions, prevention specialists, school programs, screening
        protocols, helplines, and referral networks — is the natural home
        for gambling prevention. Gambling-specific support is available
        through the <strong>National Problem Gambling Helpline</strong> at
        <a href="tel:18006973738">1-800-MY-RESET (1-800-697-3738)</a>, and
        crisis support through <a href="tel:988">988</a>, providing
        ready-made referral endpoints for screening that turns up risk.
      </p>

      <h3>Center equity and at-risk populations</h3>
      <p>
        The populations that carry elevated gambling risk — younger
        people, those with lower income and socioeconomic status, people
        with co-occurring substance-use or mental-health conditions, and
        people with histories of trauma and adversity — are, by and
        large, the same populations carrying elevated risk across
        behavioral health (SAMHSA, 2014; Poole et al., 2017; Sundqvist
        &amp; Wennberg, 2021). Comprehensive, integrated prevention that
        reaches these shared-risk groups advances equity precisely
        because it addresses clustered, co-occurring burdens together
        rather than asking already-stretched individuals and communities
        to navigate separate systems for each condition.
      </p>

      <h2>Key takeaways</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Gambling disorder is classified as a <strong>behavioral
          addiction</strong> in DSM-5 / DSM-5-TR, sharing reward-system
          neurobiology and mechanisms with substance use disorders.</li>
        <li><strong>Co-occurrence is the norm:</strong> about 96 percent of
          people with lifetime pathological gambling have another
          psychiatric disorder, and roughly 64 percent have three or more
          (Kessler et al., 2008). Substance use, mood, anxiety, attention,
          and personality conditions all co-occur at elevated rates.</li>
        <li><strong>Suicide risk is elevated</strong> and is closely tied
          to co-occurring conditions and financial crisis; gambling
          belongs in suicide-prevention awareness, and 988 and
          1-800-MY-RESET offer support.</li>
        <li>Gambling shares <strong>risk and protective factors</strong> —
          impulsivity, early onset, trauma / ACEs, reward neurobiology;
          connectedness, coping skills, accurate risk understanding — with
          other behavioral-health conditions.</li>
        <li>The practical upshot is <strong>integrated prevention</strong>:
          screen for gambling (Lie/Bet, BBGS, SBIRT-style models), embed
          it in existing substance-use and mental-health systems, and
          reach shared-risk populations to advance equity.</li>
      </ul>

